SIMPLE: oracle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Oracle
<hw>Or"a*cle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>oraculum</ets>, fr. <ets>orare</ets> to speak, utter, pray, fr.
<ets>os</ets>, <ets>oris</ets>, mouth. See <er>Oral</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The answer of a god, or some person reputed to be a
god, to an inquiry respecting some affair or future event, as the
success of an enterprise or battle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whatso'er she saith, for <qex>oracles</qex> must stand.</q>
<rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>The deity who was supposed
to give the answer; also, the place where it was given.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>oracles</qex> are dumb;⟦br⟧
No voice or hideous hum⟦br⟧
Runs through the arched roof in words deceiving.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The communications, revelations, or messages
delivered by God to the prophets; also, the entire sacred Scriptures --
usually in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The first principles of the <qex>oracles</qex> of God.</q>
<rj><qau>Heb. v. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Jewish Antiq.)</fld> <def>The sanctuary, or Most
Holy place in the temple; also, the temple itself.</def> <rj><au>1 Kings
vi. 19.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Siloa's brook, that flow'd⟦br⟧
Fast by the <qex>oracle</qex> of God.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>One who communicates an oracle{1} or divine command;
an angel; a prophet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God hath now sent his living <qex>oracle</qex>⟦br⟧
Into the world to teach his final will.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Any person reputed uncommonly wise; one whose
decisions are regarded as of great authority; <as>as, a literary
<ex>oracle</ex></as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Oracles</xex> of mode.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The country rectors . . . thought him an <qex>oracle</qex> on
points of learning.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A wise pronouncement or decision considered as of
great authority.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oracle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Oracle
<hw>Or"a*cle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Oracled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Oracling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To utter
oracles.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oracular</ent>⟦br⟧
